<DOC><DOCNO> AP891121-0193 </DOCNO><FILEID>AP-NR-11-21-89 2149EST</FILEID><FIRST>r a AM-WedtechIndictment     11-21 0269</FIRST><SECOND>AM-Wedtech Indictment,0276</SECOND><HEAD>Former Army Employee Charged In Wedtech Scandal</HEAD><BYLINE>By VERA HALLER</BYLINE><BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE><DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE><TEXT>   Federal prosecutors in the Wedtech Corp. scandalunsealed an indictment Tuesday charging a former Army employee withtaking more than $569,000 in bribes from officials of thenow-defunct defense contractor.   The indictment said the defendant, Gordon Osgood Sr., reviewedWedtech's performance on Army contracts while he was a civilianemployee at the Army's Tank Automotive Command in Warren, Mich.   Prosecutors allege Osgood received more than $569,000 in illegalpayoffs from Wedtech officials between 1980 and 1985 in exchangefor favorable performance evaluations, confidential Army contractinformation and help with receiving advance payments. The companyalso allegedly provided Osgood, 66, of Romeo, Mich., with use of aleased Mercedes-Benz in 1984 and 1985.   Osgood's attorney, Robert Gray, refused to discuss the charges,saying his client hadn't yet been informed about them.   Osgood was charged in a 13-count indictment with racketeering,conspiracy, accepting bribes and illegal gratuities, conspiracy andtax evasion. He is scheduled for arraignment in federal court Nov.30.   The newest charges were approved by a federal grand jury inApril but were kept secret until Tuesday, said U.S. Attorney OttoObermaier.   Evidence at earlier trials showed Wedtech, once a small SouthBronx machine shop, grew into a multimillion-dollar militarycontractor through various bribe schemes. The company collapsed inDecember 1986 amid allegations of corruption.   Among those convicted in previous Wedtech cases were U.S. Rep.Robert Garcia, D-Bronx, and his wife, former Rep. Mario Biaggi andE. Robert Wallach, a close friend of ex-U.S. Attorney General EdwinMeese.</TEXT></DOC>